text: Dear Universal Pictures,  I get this has nothing to do with this movie but, I wanna see a remake of the movie called Gingerclown.  Trailer for Gingerclown: https://youtu.be/3YJt5WmXPW8  The reasons I wanna see a remake of this movie is because it was released in 2012 but made in 1980 style. The monsters were puppeteered, no explanation why the monsters are at the abandoned park in the first place or how they were made or where they came from or why they eat human flesh. Plus the script was poorly written and it just has a healthy dose of dumb. And the scene where the jock dies, I don‚Äôt understand how all his skin came off just by getting spun in circles on a ride. And the one scene with the spider, literally a shotgun came straight out of nowhere. For real. There‚Äôs a lot of scenes I don‚Äôt understand and I feel like this movie really deserves a remake with better scripting, better actors, better monsters (like use CGI and not puppets), plus an explanation on how the monsters  were created and why they eat humans. If it does end up getting remade, I‚Äôd be okay if you guys worked on remaking this film with Blumhouse. Plus for actors, I‚Äôd like to see Samara Weaving play Jenny, Robbie Amell as Sam, Chris Hemsworth as Biff, Bill Skarsg√•rd as Gingerclown, Mark Hamill as Wormface, and Fiona Dourif as Nelly the Spiderwoman. Please think about it. I‚Äôd really like to see a better version of this movie.  ‚ÄîSincerely, A Universal Studios Fan.

text: I really do not know what to make of this trailer. On the one hand, being stalked is a very real thing, that is truly horrifying and difficult to deal with, so making the stalker a literal movie monster is really upping the horror of that situation, and it seems they are going for a Rosemary's Baby type of horror, where no one believes the protagonist as well, which is a very effective type of horror. On the other hand, it's rather odd to see a Universal movie monster with the (apparently) singular goal of just ruining one persons life. If the women being stalked dies or disappears, does the Invisible Man have to get a new girlfriend to continue obsessing over, or is he just done? It also seems like a pretty solvable problem, unless for some reason the woman being stalked here has no friends or credibility at all, or the Invisible Man has other super-powers. It will be interesting to see if the writer is really creative, or just lazy.

text: This is odd.  It‚Äôs made by Universal and Blumhouse, so with Universal owning the rights and being involved, one would think this would be a modern remake of the original ‚ÄúThe Invisible Man‚Äù ... but it‚Äôs not.  This is a totally different story.  It‚Äôs got the characters‚Äô names, but Mr. Invisible wasn‚Äôt like a super bad guy in the original.  This just turns him into a stalker, a pretty obvious and typical story to use an invisible man in.  I just find all this kind of odd, but at the same time, the original always stood out in the Universal Monsters lineup bc he was never really a monster.  So in essence, this change makes a lot of sense and can finally make The Invisible Man into a real horror movie.  Don‚Äôt know what to think of all this, but it doesn‚Äôt bother me, I just hope it‚Äôs good.

text: This movie was awesome..I absolutely loved it. Never has an Invisible Man movie been so scary. It was almost like a possession or haunting film, especially with the orchestrated soundtrack. This is a must see film. We just got out of the movies earlier!!  My friend Glenn went with me and my wife to the show. This brand new The Invisible Man that came out yesterday was the best movie I've seen in a while! Absolutely awesome film. They turned the idea of The Invisible Man into a very violent and scary story you would not expect. It also has a very wicked orchestrated soundtrack reminiscent of an older horror film. It sends chills down your spine. The storyline is how the wife of a psychopathical scientist who developes high tech experimental gadgetry, stalks her in invisible form, after convincing everyone of his death,  and terrorizes her, after she flees their home in the middle of the night to escape him, since he is terrorizing in her everyday life as well. She soon realizes he is not dead, but invisible and hunting her. There are scenes after he finds her where she is being held up off the ground and beaten by this invisible man, kind of like in the old thriller The Entity or a demonic possession thriller. He kills people violently and blames it on her. She ends up being committed to an insane asylum since everyone thinks she's imagining it. But eventually she finds a way to fight back. This movie was awesome!!! I give it 10 out 10 skulls..üíÄüíÄüíÄüíÄüíÄüíÄüíÄüíÄüíÄüíÄ

text: TRYING HARD NOT TO SPOIL HEREüòä -   For me...Another favorite piece of literature! But not sure exactly how I feel about the entertainment of this movie. Some parts of the story lacked, and the guy ACTOR in the house "AT THE DINNER TABLE" seriously, seriously lacked luster once he spoke... The movie is good, but it didn't keep my constant interest throughout!¬† So I wouldn't say, "It's a must see" if you want an exciting storyline, but if there's nothing better out, then go see this! I just think there were other ways to make this storyline interesting throughout!¬† HOWEVER!!!¬† I DID really enjoyed the modern spin on this book!¬† The innovative idea of creating an invisible ("Blank" - trying not to spoil here) is extremely interesting and it felt realistic, bc it makes you think due to our advancement of technology its quite possible that one day someone may actually be able to create such a futuristic "blank" in the near future!¬† Perhaps One Will Never KnowüòÑ, but its a thought!¬† Well anyway, "IF ONLY" for the parts with the great "blank"üòä, the lab, the adorable dog, and ESPECIALLY to see how this actual "blank" works, then for these reasons alone the movie is a must see‚ò∫!

text: Okay, decent movie... but here‚Äôs where they f*cked up: Frankenstein just wants peace, the creature from the black lagoon just wants love, the wolf man just wants control, Dracula just wants life... and the Invisible man... the black sheep of the family (which is why Universal probably spared his licensing at low risk to a 7 million production... nobody‚Äôs been really able to crack that code) but for now, let‚Äôs just say he wants to be seen... my point is... yes, they‚Äôre all villains but the universal monsters are all, to varying degrees, sympathetic characters... and this movie wasn‚Äôt about the invisible man, it was about his victim... I won‚Äôt get too far into the ‚Äòculture war‚Äô aspects of this film, I will spare this comments section that endless debate... but... I am glad Blumhouse has taken the reigns, at the very least, they produce quality work... but I also believe the inexperience of the Director becomes apparent right around the time the third act falls completely to pieces... and not to mention important themes were completely missed in favor of pursuing a rather blunt tale of female empowerment

She apparently sends a hateful email to sister which she never did. She gets blamed for "kicking" james daughter She looks for answers on invisible man. Finds adrian phone in James attic. She throws paint and there is the invisible man.  She fights invisible man. Escapes. She goes to Adrian's house for clues. She finds a suit that creates an optical illusion of surrounds covering the wearer of its surroundings giving the illusion of invisibility. Something out of mysterios wardrobe.  She tries to tell sister in fancy restaurant. Sisters neck gets slit with chef knife by invisible man. She gets blamed for it and gos into psych institute. Stuff happens. Invisible suit give wearer the strength to fight 7 guards. She manages to shoot mysterio. Mysterio tells her cliche and goes after james daughter. She tells james to go home. James goes home. Mysterio is there and attempts to fight james daughter and him. She comes and shoots invisible man 3 times. Turns out it was Adrian's brother cosplaying as mysterio. Turns out adrian was really alive and didnt commit suicide. Stuff happens.  She has dinner with adrian.  Adrian neck gets slit by chef knife by invisible man after struggling to keep knife away, but the suit gives inhuman strength. She was the one who killed him with the suit. James knew she did but kept it to himself. Credits roll.  The end.

text: Saw it today. It's as lifeless and artless as you can expect (the title may as well refer to Whannell), often to hilarity, with an exceptionally poor script being being carried by it's two leads (and a strong cast who deserve far better). Moss is brilliant (and worth the price of admission alone)  gives the film a heart and conviction beyond Whannell and Oliver Jackson-Cohen desperately searches for any kind of nuance (and this is the man who surrived The Haunting of Hill House finale) in vain, but pushes himself to match Moss, despite his surroundings.    While Wan's days in Hollywood are numbered and we don't need Whannell climbing back up the ranks, I'm really hoping whoever actually originated this take makes their way through.

text: Oh my goodness! I wanted to hate this movie so much after reading the title of it. I for sure thought it was going to be cheesy but this was A_Awesome! It was a very well put together movie. The use of "modern/futuristic" technology gave it it's own sense of added horror to the mix. It gives the viewer that extra edge of creepy by influencing the thought of such thing existing amongst us this very moment or at least century. That's what blew my mind most about this movie! Well, finally after many years, I'm now replacing a movie from "Top 5 All Time Favorite Movies!" hands down!  If you don't won't to read any spoilers...READ NO FURTHER.....  What I think made me love this movie so much was how the Director, writer or whomever (thank you whomever that is) made it happen....to whereas, the movie could've split off into at least two diff maybe even three possible timelines. Now I may be high as hell rn but hear me out okay. Lol, alright, now.....OMG Yoooo. I had to pause for a few minutes to actually watch the trailer and let me tell you something! For the first time in a while, I'm glad I watched a movie before the trailer. There were some scenes that weren't in the movie that were in the trailer and there were scenes shown in the trailer that weren't in the final cut of the movie! I'm sure they were moved into the "Extras" on Blu-Ray and what not but that's not my point. Watching that trailer right after the movie was like watching a short of short-film in in-itself. A blast all over again but in one big rush all at once! Phew....alright, back to my original comment. How the movie could've changed into different directions...SPOILER ALERT AGAIN....At one hour, twenty-six minutes, and thirteen seconds into the movie is a scene where Cecilia's standing in the shower of her cell within the psych-ward that she has been emitted into impales her wrist with a fountain pen and begins to slice downward after saying aloud, "You won't get the baby and you won't get me!"...I hate to interrupt this program but SPOILER ALERT again....If Cecilia's boyfriend Adrian had killed that last officer (even though this officer wasn't used or even shown later on in the movie) he could've been a witness to her case had she been seized and "captured" again. That being he told the truth and the jury and judge believe him...then you have the trails and blah, blah, blah... Okay so then you also have an alternate route where Cecilia kills Adrian and all, well, most (being as though the use of his brother isn't immediately known yet) of the evidence she'd need to plead innocent in her case would be present and accountable for. Followed by trials and blah..blah..blah....Alright, now stick with me just a bit longer alright......ah crap. My high is coming down now and my what I think at least is a "creative writing style", is starting to die down. But another scene where things could've taken for a turn is at 1:47:57.....this is where Adrian is hinted to be revealing himself to the audience right before the big scene! This announcement was presented in a way that's like a strong undertone. While not quite sitting on the surface level but by subconsciously insinuating that he was indeed the original "Invisible Man". And this is in fact the case as followed by the upcoming scene (The revenge) But what also backs this is up at 1:48:07...."the change in pitch". The sound engineers emphasized Adrian saying, "I mean ugh...that shouldn't come as ugh...SURPRISE." And then the horrifying, heart wrenching laughter followed by tears of rejoice relay that she, "Cecelia", had also picked up on this. In fact, she well has may have wished, and hoped for that to be the case as she planned her night ending accordingly. I saw it coming but then again, I really didn't and that too was just great! I could go on an on but I should go. Anyway's there were also scenes in trailer that I mentioned earlier that were shown in the trailer but not in the movie. One, being the hand-print being created on the glass shower door or the pronounced breathing effect being blown next to Cecelia when standing on the front porch of Jame's home as seen here at 1:10 in this video. Man....this is one of those movies that would've been perfect to watch in theaters since you'd have those moments where you'd hear the gasp sounds of a few or even maybe a large group of people picking up on ques within the movie. Or hearing the sounds of potential others expressing the same amount of excitement over the movie as you are! Damn you corona! Anyway's it's 2AM. I'm going to take my tired high ass to sleep now. Hopefully this comment is able to be shared and found amusing by others!    Also, one tip, (If possible) watch this movie with your volume being comfortably set higher than you normally listen at. I believe this to be a contributing factor to the amount of immersiveness that I was doused in while watching this movie.

text: People talking about how he invented something world changing and used it to follow a girl. Pshhh.. Elisabeth Moss is beautiful and anyone would become obsessed to an unhealthy degree... Kidding! Joking aside, abusive people aren't stable or rational people. They come to think of their partners, family, and kids as their property and will do insane things to keep them... even if they don't seem to want them, considering how they treat them. They see someone leaving them as a humiliation and HAVE to make them pay for that humiliation.  I dated a girl in highschool whose father was abusive and sexually abused her as a kid. She was from Seattle and we lived in Florida, and he broke out of jail in Oregon and came _all the way across the country_ to stalk her at our highschool! Apparently it was my fault! Her mother told him she finally moved on with her life and was happy with a nice guy and that just broke this sick fucker. He was so enraged that his daughter was dating that he broke out of fucking jail! He then went to the one obvious place, assaulted 3 minors, got attempted murder on a teacher, and set a car on fire. We think he thought it was my car... because it was an Acura also, and I drove an '09 Acura TSX, he burned a faculty members car and when he ran out to see what happened this dude beat him with a wrench or something... almost killed him! (He was a good science teacher too.. nice dude.)  Our parents gave us a thousand bucks and told me to just drive and not tell them where and not to text, and wait for them to contact us. We went to Orlando and had to stay there for 9 days before they caught him.. he was caught at the school trying to offer students alcohol and drugs for information to where her friends lived. Friggin psycho!  Those types of people are fucking insane and will never act in a logical way. If a guy like that had access to invisibility I'm 100% sure he would use it.  I still haven't watched this movie because that type of situation makes me very uncomfortable, it's kinda personal for me. It looks amazing though, and got good reviews so I might finally watch it!

text: So I watched this film the other day and I thought it was iiiight. I mean, it was better than the kevin bacon version from 20 years ago, that's for sure, but really it was a forgettable film that I probably won't ever bother watching again. The real shocking part about this movie is the inexplicable Rotten Tomatoes aggregate score of *92%* *92 fucking percent* Now how how does that RT score compare to some of the greatest films of all time? Jurassic Park - 91% Gladiator - 77% Pulp Fiction - 91% Forrest Gump - 70% Braveheart -  77% Shawshank Redemption - 90% Casino - 80% Heat - 86% Charlie and the Chocolate Factory (1971)  - 91% The Shining - 85% Blade Runner- 90% Blood Diamond - 63% The Departed - 91% These are some of the greatest movies of all time....all of which I have re-watched many many times.  I mean hell, even The original Star Wars from 1977 received a score of 92% the same score as "the invisible man". *Fucking Star Wars* is as good as the invisible man ü§î..... Are you serious right now? üòÇüòÇüòÇ
